{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17623847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17623847"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:13:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:13:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16879"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16879"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.85,0.07,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9569"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67444"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9569","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9569"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16879"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52896"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4903"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9858"},{"type":"tags","id":"9863"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22590"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22597"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67444","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67444"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes cardiac preload?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Resistance against which the ventricle must pump","End-diastolic volume that stretches the ventricle before contraction","Rate of ventricular filling during diastole","Force of contraction of the cardiac muscle","Pressure generated during ventricular ejection"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnd-diastolic volume that stretches the ventricle before contraction\u003C/strong\u003E correctly defines preload. This stretching of cardiac muscle fibres before contraction determines the force of contraction through the Frank-Starling mechanism.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EResistance against which the ventricle must pump\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes afterload, not preload\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForce of contraction of the cardiac muscle\u003C/strong\u003E - This is contractility, which is influenced by but distinct from preload\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERate of ventricular filling during diastole\u003C/strong\u003E - While this affects preload, it is not preload itself\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPressure generated during ventricular ejection\u003C/strong\u003E - This is related to afterload and contractility, not preload\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EPreload is primarily determined by venous return to the heart. Changes in blood volume, posture, and venous tone can all affect preload and consequently influence cardiac output through the Frank-Starling mechanism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Preload refers to the end-diastolic volume that stretches the ventricle before contraction.","According to the Frank-Starling mechanism, increased preload leads to increased stroke volume up to a physiological limit.","Venous return is the main determinant of cardiac preload."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisi